<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="556" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,259,1042]" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,267,259,285]" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1858" box="[277,532,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Castolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="556" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plagiaticollis">
<emphasis box="[277,532,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">Castolus plagiaticollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a conspicuous species with red head, red femora, dark tibiae, a large ovoid marking on the posterior lobe of the pronotum, mostly yellowish corium and clavus with the apex of the corium black, and a black membrane except its apex which is translucent (
<bibRefCitation author="Maldonado, J." box="[921,1119,331,358]" pageId="18" pageNumber="556" pagination="435 - 446" refId="ref15942" refString="Maldonado, J. (1976) Three new species of Castolus and a key to the species (Hemiptera: Reduviidae). Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 78, 435 - 446. https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / part / 56099" type="journal article" year="1976">Maldonado 1976</bibRefCitation>
). Nonetheless, it is variable regarding its hemelytral color pattern. 
<bibRefCitation author="Champion, G. C." box="[582,781,367,393]" pageId="18" pageNumber="556" refId="ref15095" refString="Champion, G. C. (1899) Insecta Rhynchota. Hemiptera-Heteroptera. Vol II. In: Godman, F. D. &amp; Salvin, F. D. (Eds.), Biologia Centrali Americana. Taylor &amp; Francis, London, pp. i - xvi + 1 - 416, 22 pls. https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 14631" type="url" year="1899">Champion (1899)</bibRefCitation>
had already mentioned that some specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[1351,1437,367,393]" name="Mexico" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">Mexico</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[198,319,403,429]" name="Guatemala" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
had a more darkened clavus and corium.Among the specimens examined and the observations from iNaturalist (https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?place_id=any&amp;q=castolus%20plagiaticollis), several instead of a yellow corium have a whitish one; a few ones have a more extended dark area on the apex of the corium, reaching in some specimens almost half the corial length, or on the other hand have a completely yellow corium without dark areas. Very rarely, the specimens have a mostly black corium being yellow only the costal area and the base of clavus. Because color patterns are important to delimit species in 
<taxonomicName authority="(Maldonado 1976)" baseAuthorityName="Maldonado" baseAuthorityYear="1976" box="[968,1283,583,610]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Castolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="556" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[968,1066,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">Castolus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Maldonado, J." box="[1080,1276,583,610]" pageId="18" pageNumber="556" pagination="435 - 446" refId="ref15942" refString="Maldonado, J. (1976) Three new species of Castolus and a key to the species (Hemiptera: Reduviidae). Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington, 78, 435 - 446. https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / part / 56099" type="journal article" year="1976">Maldonado 1976</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, the observed color variation in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1858" box="[357,540,619,646]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Castolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="556" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plagiaticollis">
<emphasis box="[357,540,619,646]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">C. plagiaticollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
highlights the importance of understanding the intraspecific color variation to adequately assess the specific limits for other species in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Maldonado" baseAuthorityYear="1976" box="[782,880,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Castolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="556" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[782,880,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">Castolus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,259,1042]" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">
<bibRefCitation author="Quiroz, J. A. &amp; Carmona, M. A. L." box="[199,494,691,717]" pageId="18" pageNumber="556" pagination="25 - 44" refId="ref16346" refString="Quiroz, J. A. &amp; Carmona, M. A. L. (2011) Harpactorinae (Hemiptera: Reduviidae) del Museo Entomologico &quot; Francisco Luis Gallego &quot; de la Universidad Nacional de Colombia, sede Medellin. Boletin de, Museo Entomologico Francisco Luis Gallego, 3 (1), 25 - 44. https: // ciencias. medellin. unal. edu. co / museos / entomologico / images / Boletin / 2011 - 03 / 4. pdf" type="journal article" year="2011">Quiroz &amp; Carmona (2011)</bibRefCitation>
listed 
<specimenCount box="[567,732,691,718]" pageId="18" pageNumber="556" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1858" box="[882,1062,691,718]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Castolus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="556" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plagiaticollis">
<emphasis box="[882,1062,691,718]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">C. plagiaticollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from MEFLG. We examined two additional specimens from MEFLG and corroborated their initial identification. The examined Colombian specimens all have a yellow corium and small apical dark area on the corium.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="556" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,259,1042]" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,799,825]" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">Distribution</emphasis>
. Originally described from 
<collectingCountry box="[667,753,799,825]" name="Mexico" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Stal, C." box="[770,883,799,826]" pageId="18" pageNumber="556" pagination="433 - 454" refId="ref16604" refString="Stal, C. (1858) Hemipterologiska bidrag. Ofversigt af Kongliga Vetenskaps-Akademiens Forhandlingar, 15, 433 - 454. https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / page / 15959503" type="journal article" year="1858">Stål 1858</bibRefCitation>
), with subsequent records from 
<collectingCountry box="[1254,1363,799,825]" name="Honduras" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">Honduras</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Maldonado, J." pageId="18" pageNumber="556" refId="ref15992" refString="Maldonado, J. (1990) Systematic catalogue of the Reduviidae of the World. Caribbean Journal of Science, Special publication No. 1. University of Puerto Rico, Mayaguez, x + 694 pp." type="book" year="1990">Maldonado 1990</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[322,446,835,861]" name="Guatemala" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">Guatemala</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[506,595,836,862]" name="Panama" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">Panama</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Champion, G. C." box="[610,796,835,861]" pageId="18" pageNumber="556" refId="ref15095" refString="Champion, G. C. (1899) Insecta Rhynchota. Hemiptera-Heteroptera. Vol II. In: Godman, F. D. &amp; Salvin, F. D. (Eds.), Biologia Centrali Americana. Taylor &amp; Francis, London, pp. i - xvi + 1 - 416, 22 pls. https: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 14631" type="url" year="1899">Champion 1899</bibRefCitation>
). It represents the first formal record of the species from South America, and a new country record from 
<collectingCountry box="[702,815,871,897]" name="Colombia" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, extending the known distribution into South America (
<figureCitation box="[160,263,907,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="19.[151,250,1556,1580]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,777,1533]" captionTargetId="figure-210@19.[151,1435,777,1533]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="FIGURE 10. Distribution map of Castolus species based on data from examined specimens and iNaturalist observations. A. C. multicintus Stål, 1872; B. C. pallidus Maldonado, 1976; C. C. plagiaticollis Stål, 1858; D. C. rufomarginatus Champion, 1899." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5556798" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5556798/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="556">Fig. 10C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
